### Description

Hello. Reading the tutorial for the new angular.dev path, in the [Property Binding](https://angular.dev/tutorials/learn-angular/property-binding) section, I saw the following code.

```js
import {Component} from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  styleUrls: ['app.component.css'],
  template: `
    <div [contentEditable]="isEditable"></div>
  `,
  standalone: true,
})
export class AppComponent {
  isEditable = true;
}
```

### Proposed solution

To make it easier, I suggest a shortened form when the element's attribute matches the class property name:

The code would look like this:

```js
import {Component} from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  styleUrls: ['app.component.css'],
  template: `
    <div [contentEditable]></div> // Shorthand property
  `,
  standalone: true,
})
export class AppComponent {
  contentEditable = true;
}
```

### Alternatives considered

When the elements repeat with the same attribute, you could do it like this:

```js
import {Component} from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  styleUrls: ['app.component.css'],
  template: `
    <div [contentEditable].first></div>
    <div [contentEditable].second></div>
  `,
  standalone: true,
})
export class AppComponent {
  contentEditable = {first: true, second: false}
}
```

or the standard mode

```js
import {Component} from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  styleUrls: ['app.component.css'],
  template: `
    <div [contentEditable]="isEditable"></div>
    <div [contentEditable]="isEditable2"></div>
  `,
  standalone: true,
})
export class AppComponent {
  isEditable = true;
  isEditable2 = true;
}
```

### Describe the problem that you experienced

Happens thrice in "Injection Context". Doesn't cause any errors, but eh. 

Code-block example:

```ts
@Component({...})
export class EffectiveCounterCmp {
  readonly count = signal(0);
  constructor() {
    // Register a new effect.
    effect(() => {
      console.log(`The count is: ${this.count()})`);
    });
  }
}
```

The extra parenthesis is here:
```ts
console.log(`The count is: ${this.count()})`);
```

